  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I create a page for a company in Wikipedia?",
  "response": "Creating a Wikipedia page for a company requires careful adherence to Wikipedia's guidelines to ensure the page meets the platform's standards for notability, neutrality, and verifiability. Here's a step-by-step guide:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Determine Notability**\n   - Wikipedia requires that a company meets its **notability guidelines** to have its own page. A company is typically considered notable if it has received significant coverage in **reliable, independent, secondary sources** (e.g., newspapers, journals, books).\n   - Coverage should be substantial and not just promotional or self-published (e.g., press releases, company websites).\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Research and Gather Sources**\n   - Identify **reliable sources** that discuss the company in detail, such as articles in reputable publications, industry reports, or academic references.\n   - Avoid using primary sources (e.g., the company\u2019s own website or marketing materials) as the sole basis for the article.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Create a Wikipedia Account**\n   - Sign up for a Wikipedia account if you don\u2019t already have one. This allows you to contribute and create pages.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Draft the Article**\n   - Use the **Article Wizard** (accessible from the Wikipedia homepage) to guide you through the process of creating a new page.\n   - Follow Wikipedia\u2019s **manual of style** to ensure the article is structured properly. A typical company page includes:\n     - **Introduction**: A brief overview of the company (e.g., industry, founding year, headquarters).\n     - **History**: Key milestones and events in the company\u2019s development.\n     - **Products/Services**: A description of what the company offers.\n     - **Operations**: Geographic presence, subsidiaries, or notable partnerships.\n     - **Controversies** (if applicable): Neutral coverage of any controversies or legal issues.\n     - **References**: Citations to reliable sources to support the information.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Write in a Neutral Tone**\n   - Wikipedia articles must be written from a **neutral point of view (NPOV)**. Avoid promotional language or exaggeration.\n   - Stick to factual information and avoid subjective claims.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Add Citations**\n   - Every statement made in the article must be verifiable and supported by **reliable sources**. Use inline citations to link to the sources.\n   - Use the <ref> tag to add citations. For example:\n     ```\n     The company was founded in 2005.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Smith |first=John |date=2005-01-15 |title=New Tech Startup Launches |url=https://example.com |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n     ```\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Submit the Draft**\n   - If you\u2019re new to Wikipedia, submit your draft for review through the **Articles for Creation (AfC)** process. This ensures the page meets Wikipedia\u2019s standards before being published.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Monitor and Update**\n   - Once the page is live, monitor it for edits or comments from other Wikipedia editors.\n   - Keep the page updated with new information, ensuring all claims are properly cited.\n\n---\n\n### Important Notes:\n   - **Conflict of Interest (COI)**: If you are affiliated with the company (e.g., an employee or owner), disclose your relationship and avoid editing the page directly. Instead, suggest edits through the talk page or seek help from an independent editor.\n   - **Deletion Risk**: Pages that do not meet Wikipedia\u2019s notability guidelines or contain promotional content are likely to be deleted.\n\n---\n\nBy following these steps and adhering to Wikipedia\u2019s policies, you can create a compliant and informative page for the company. If you\u2019re unsure about any part of the process, consider consulting experienced Wikipedia editors for assistance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
